  "prompt": "Who invented the English alphabet?",
  "response": "The English alphabet as we know it today evolved over time and was influenced by several alphabets. It can be traced back to the Latin alphabet, which was used by the Romans. The Latin alphabet originated from the Greek alphabet, which in turn was derived from the Phoenician alphabet.\n\nThe modern English alphabet, consisting of 26 letters, was standardized in the 16th century during the time of William Shakespeare. The letter \"J\" was the last addition to the alphabet and was first distinguished from the letter \"I\" in the 17th century.\n\nIn conclusion, no single person invented the English alphabet. Instead, it evolved over time through the contributions of many civilizations and cultures.",
